1
00:00:00,058 --> 00:00:03,453
[AI-generated narration] Backup success is not recovery success.

2
00:00:03,453 --> 00:00:07,262
ProofRestore verifies recovery before an emergency.

3
00:00:07,262 --> 00:00:08,949
I’ll open the demo vault.

4
00:00:08,949 --> 00:00:18,149
The latest backup completed, but recoverability is at risk: eight snapshots hide two integrity issues and a retention risk.

5
00:00:18,149 --> 00:00:19,349
I’ll check a file.

6
00:00:19,349 --> 00:00:22,750
The request asks for my thesis from Tuesday evening.

7
00:00:22,750 --> 00:00:28,154
Its history shows damaged recent versions and a verified Tuesday copy.

8
00:00:28,154 --> 00:00:33,334
I’ll keep the interpreted time, choose the original location, and verify.

9
00:00:33,334 --> 00:00:40,886
Deterministic code selects the eligible snapshot, finds the stored object, and proves its hash and size.

10
00:00:40,886 --> 00:00:43,549
This version is fully recoverable.

11
00:00:43,549 --> 00:00:46,356
The restore simulation changes nothing.

12
00:00:46,356 --> 00:00:53,224
A newer destination file would conflict, so ProofRestore protects it instead of overwriting it.

13
00:00:53,224 --> 00:01:01,344
These evidence entries trace the snapshot, path, object, matching hash and size, and conflict.

14
00:01:01,344 --> 00:01:08,567
The downloaded proof report preserves the request, verdict, plan, methodology, and appendix.

15
00:01:08,567 --> 00:01:11,414
Anyone can test the same engine directly.

16
00:01:11,414 --> 00:01:19,625
The Recovery Lab reads selected files locally and changes only in-memory copies—nothing is uploaded or modified.

17
00:01:19,625 --> 00:01:24,238
I’ll load the sample, corrupt one stored copy, and run the check.

18
00:01:24,238 --> 00:01:28,404
The ordered log exposes every snapshot and byte change.

19
00:01:28,404 --> 00:01:35,641
The fixed expected hash and changed observed hash produce hash mismatch and an unrecoverable result.

20
00:01:35,641 --> 00:01:44,762
You can choose your own files or folder, remove an object, create a conflict, export the manifest, or continue through the full workflow.

21
00:01:44,762 --> 00:01:50,285
Natural language interprets requests, but deterministic code decides recovery.

22
00:01:50,285 --> 00:01:53,000
Backups should not require faith.

23
00:01:56,850 --> 00:02:03,118
ProofRestore was developed during OpenAI Build Week with Codex and GPT-5.6.

24
00:02:03,118 --> 00:02:13,356
Codex helped shape the architecture, implement the deterministic recovery engine and Recovery Lab,
build adversarial tests, refine accessibility, and run release validation.

25
00:02:13,356 --> 00:02:18,288
AI interprets intent, but deterministic code alone decides recovery.
